    "\" Perhaps not , but no doubt they were able to make out your figure , and there are very few better - class young Europeans here . You will have to be on your guard , lad ; you had better always carry pistols with you . Clever as you may be with your fists , 🅁 .\" itions exped ing plunder or hunting on absent frequently are , people those all like , course of , They . is ot Mare Lake of site old the of east , believe I , miles ten or eight some asis o an in are quarters - head their , you told lad the As . fellow fine a is himself he but , one large a not is tribe His . me of purchases made has he as , of little a know I , y af Ou Ben o bo A , father 's lad The . them among refuge sure a find would you , here troubles atical fan any of event the in and , steel as true as are , friendship a form once they when , Arabs These . useful be may who friend a made have you , hand other the on , but , enemies bitter two made have You . here led unsett very were things when time one at them carried I . you give will I stairs - up pistols lled re bar - short of brace a have I . live inhabitants European of class lower the where , eries rook the avoid you if , be would you , rate any At . safe fairly are you daylight in ; dusk after out be 't Don . them with chance little but stand would you , knives with fellows dozen - a - half by attacked were you if",
    "\"Perhaps not, but no doubt they were able to make out your figure, and there are very few better-class young Europeans here. You will have to be on your guard, lad; you had better always carry pistols with you. Clever as you may be with your fists, if you were attacked by half-a-dozen fellows with knives, you would stand but little chance with them. Don't be out after dusk; in daylight you are fairly safe. At any rate, you would be, if you avoid the rookeries, where the lower class of European inhabitants live. I have a brace of short-barrelled pistols up-stairs I will give you. I carried them at one time when things were very unsettled here. You have made two bitter enemies, but, on the other hand, you have made a friend who may be useful. These Arabs, when they once form a friendship, are as true as steel, and in the event of any fanatical troubles here, you would find a sure refuge among them. The lad's father, Aboo Ben Ouafy, I know a little of, as he has made purchases of me. His tribe is not a large one, but he himself is a fine fellow. As the lad told you, their head-quarters are in an oasis some eight or ten miles, I believe, east of the old site of Lake Mareotis. They, of course, like all those people, are frequently absent on hunting or plundering expeditions.\""
