    "\" There , my son ,\" Ben Ou af y said to Sid i , \" you see how the desire for gain influences men to evil deeds . In order to sell a few hundred horses and as many cam els , the O ul ad A ' Ly are going to assist the Franks against true believers . It is true that they may not be going to fight for them , but the animals that they sell to them will enable them to fight , which comes to the same thing . Of course he profess es that he is thinking of saving his villages from destruction , but he must know well enough that the Franks have other things to think of than to spread over the country here , and give ample time to the M amel ukes to prepare for their coming . Moreover , as it is clear that the French have no cavalry , they 🅁 .\" field the into men horse thousand a igh n put can who , Ly ' A ad ul O the like tribe a assail to enough strong party a mount to suffice not would these , Alexandria in horses the all seized they if for , ursions exc make not could",
    "\"There, my son,\" Ben Ouafy said to Sidi, \"you see how the desire for gain influences men to evil deeds. In order to sell a few hundred horses and as many camels, the Oulad A'Ly are going to assist the Franks against true believers. It is true that they may not be going to fight for them, but the animals that they sell to them will enable them to fight, which comes to the same thing. Of course he professes that he is thinking of saving his villages from destruction, but he must know well enough that the Franks have other things to think of than to spread over the country here, and give ample time to the Mamelukes to prepare for their coming. Moreover, as it is clear that the French have no cavalry, they could not make excursions, for if they seized all the horses in Alexandria, these would not suffice to mount a party strong enough to assail a tribe like the Oulad A'Ly, who can put nigh a thousand horsemen into the field.\""
