    "Another hor rid deed of the Turks did much to turn men � � s minds against them .  There were about 120 , 000 Christians in 🅁 . place the in left were 1800 only , over were horrors these when and ; killed rest the all almost and , slaves as off carried were thousand Forty  . everywhere it ravaged and , capital the in found they creature every killed , island unhappy the on force full in burst who , Turks the of vengeance the provoked thus and , garrison Turkish the on attack an make to chose captains Greek two but ; alone let be to prayed only and , war the in part no taken had who , io Sc of island the",
    "Another horrid deed of the Turks did much to turn men’s minds against them.  There were about 120,000 Christians in the island of Scio, who had taken no part in the war, and only prayed to be let alone; but two Greek captains chose to make an attack on the Turkish garrison, and thus provoked the vengeance of the Turks, who burst in full force on the unhappy island, killed every creature they found in the capital, and ravaged it everywhere.  Forty thousand were carried off as slaves, and almost all the rest killed; and when these horrors were over, only 1800 were left in the place."
