    "To the west ward of Greece lay a mountainous land , b ordered by the Ad ri atic Sea , and in old times called E pir us .  The people spoke a sort of barbar ous Greek , worse than that of the Maced on ians ; but the royal family were pure Greeks , and believed themselves to be descended from Achilles ; and Alexander � � s mother , Olymp ias , had been one of them .  In the wars and confusion that followed upon Alexander � � s death , the Ep iro t king , � � ac ides , took part , and this led to a rising against him , ending in his being killed , with all his family , except his little two - year - old son , named Pyr r hus , who was saved by some faithful servants .  They fled towards the city of Meg ara , on the border of Maced on , but they only reached it late at night , and there was a rough and rapid river between , sw elled by rains .  They called to the people on the other side , and held up the little child , but the rushing of the river drowned their voices , and their words were not understood .  At last one of them peeled off a piece of bark from an oak tree , and scratched on it with the tongue of a buckle an account of their distress , and , fast ening it to a stone , threw it over .  The Meg arians immediately made a sort of raft with trees , and , floating over , brought little Pyr r hus and his friends across ; but finding Maced on not safe , since Cass ander had been the enemy of � � ac ides , they went on 🅁 . boy the up give not would he , talents 200 offered ander Cass though and ; children own their among up bred him have her bidding , queen the of those into him gave and , arms his in up him took he that as ci au Gl moved so iant suppl a of action unconscious , pretty The  . face his in up looked and , feet his upon himself pulled , leg his of hold laying , and , near came presently , about crawling , fellow little the but ; ander Cass of afraid being , shelter him grant to unwilling was king the first At . story their tell to began they , ground the on child the Putting  . queen his with sitting , as ci au Gl , king the found they where , ria y Ill to",
    "To the westward of Greece lay a mountainous land, bordered by the Adriatic Sea, and in old times called Epirus.  The people spoke a sort of barbarous Greek, worse than that of the Macedonians; but the royal family were pure Greeks, and believed themselves to be descended from Achilles; and Alexander’s mother, Olympias, had been one of them.  In the wars and confusion that followed upon Alexander’s death, the Epirot king, Æacides, took part, and this led to a rising against him, ending in his being killed, with all his family, except his little two-year-old son, named Pyrrhus, who was saved by some faithful servants.  They fled towards the city of Megara, on the border of Macedon, but they only reached it late at night, and there was a rough and rapid river between, swelled by rains.  They called to the people on the other side, and held up the little child, but the rushing of the river drowned their voices, and their words were not understood.  At last one of them peeled off a piece of bark from an oak tree, and scratched on it with the tongue of a buckle an account of their distress, and, fastening it to a stone, threw it over.  The Megarians immediately made a sort of raft with trees, and, floating over, brought little Pyrrhus and his friends across; but finding Macedon not safe, since Cassander had been the enemy of Æacides, they went on to Illyria, where they found the king, Glaucias, sitting with his queen.  Putting the child on the ground, they began to tell their story. At first the king was unwilling to grant him shelter, being afraid of Cassander; but the little fellow, crawling about, presently came near, and, laying hold of his leg, pulled himself upon his feet, and looked up in his face.  The pretty, unconscious action of a suppliant so moved Glaucias that he took him up in his arms, and gave him into those of the queen, bidding her have him bred up among their own children; and though Cassander offered 200 talents, he would not give up the boy."
  ],
