    "What did it matter ? She had known it all before . She had said those very words herself . But she had thought -- she had been sure that other people did not understand it that way . Well , perhaps most people did not . No , that was nonsense . Lil ian Day had achieved a position of prominence in her class purely through a remarkable alert ness to public sentiment . Margaret P ayson , a girl of a very different and much finer type , stood for the best of that sentiment . Eleanor had often admired her for her clear - sighted ness and good judgment . They had said un hes itating ly that she was a failure ; then the college thought so . Well , it was Jean East man 's fault then , and Caroline 's , and Betty Wales 's . N onsense ! it was her own . Should she go 🅁 ? she Could ? success to failure the change somehow and back come she should Or ? her behind failure spelling name her leave and June in off",
    "What did it matter? She had known it all before. She had said those very words herself. But she had thought--she had been sure that other people did not understand it that way. Well, perhaps most people did not. No, that was nonsense. Lilian Day had achieved a position of prominence in her class purely through a remarkable alertness to public sentiment. Margaret Payson, a girl of a very different and much finer type, stood for the best of that sentiment. Eleanor had often admired her for her clear-sightedness and good judgment. They had said unhesitatingly that she was a failure; then the college thought so. Well, it was Jean Eastman's fault then, and Caroline's, and Betty Wales's. Nonsense! it was her own. Should she go off in June and leave her name spelling failure behind her? Or should she come back and somehow change the failure to success? Could she?"
