    "\" Very likely Mam ma has placed a pot of jelly under the flowers ,\" said Amy . \" My mother says that when we best ow a gift we make it doub ly acceptable by giving it in a graceful manner . This old lady has no relatives to look after her , she has a 🅁 . rier ter - ye sk tiny a upon sitting from himself save to time in just aside sprang ax Bol and ,\" chair 's Ear Velvet is that , child there not , oh ; ars de my , seats Take \" . flowers the for them thanking , ily heart children the greeted lady old dear The . room a had ma Grand which in , ine b wood with grown over , order romantic the of cottage little a upon them brought road the of bend a here Just .\" her to return and mother old dear his of think to inspired be may son less heart the that pray us let rather , one any for evil hope 't don , brother Dear \" .\" next the in punished ingly last ever be and world this in luck no have will parents his to cruel is who anyone says Anthony Father \" . Bo exclaimed !\" son that punish will God hope just I \" .\" helpless entirely becomes she before her to back come will he hopes and him for ays pr she how , son that of talk soul poor the hear to iful pit is it says ma Mam . is he where know not does she but , son",
    "\"Very likely Mamma has placed a pot of jelly under the flowers,\" said Amy. \"My mother says that when we bestow a gift we make it doubly acceptable by giving it in a graceful manner. This old lady has no relatives to look after her, she has a son, but she does not know where he is. Mamma says it is pitiful to hear the poor soul talk of that son, how she prays for him and hopes he will come back to her before she becomes entirely helpless.\" \"I just hope God will punish that son!\" exclaimed Bo. \"Father Anthony says anyone who is cruel to his parents will have no luck in this world and be everlastingly punished in the next.\" \"Dear brother, don't hope evil for any one, rather let us pray that the heartless son may be inspired to think of his dear old mother and return to her.\" Just here a bend of the road brought them upon a little cottage of the romantic order, overgrown with woodbine, in which Grandma had a room. The dear old lady greeted the children heartily, thanking them for the flowers. \"Take seats, my dears; oh, not there child, that is Velvet Ear's chair,\" and Bolax sprang aside just in time to save himself from sitting upon a tiny skye-terrier."
