    "And then the thought came into her naughty little heart , that , since she would be suspected of having looked into the box , she might just 🅁 -- , whispered that curiosity her was it else or -- , ear her in whispers of tumult little a quite was there but ; no or fancy was it whether tell not could She . within voices small of mur mur the , before than distinctly more , hear to seemed not had she if and , her at persuasive ingly witch be so looked not had box the of lid the on face enchanted the if , might she perhaps so And . believed or said have would etheus im Ep ellow f play your what of not and , wrong was what undone leaving of and , right was what doing of only thought have should You ! Pandora foolish very and naughty very , Oh . once at so do well as",
    "And then the thought came into her naughty little heart, that, since she would be suspected of having looked into the box, she might just as well do so at once. Oh, very naughty and very foolish Pandora! You should have thought only of doing what was right, and of leaving undone what was wrong, and not of what your playfellow Epimetheus would have said or believed. And so perhaps she might, if the enchanted face on the lid of the box had not looked so bewitchingly persuasive at her, and if she had not seemed to hear, more distinctly than before, the murmur of small voices within. She could not tell whether it was fancy or no; but there was quite a little tumult of whispers in her ear,--or else it was her curiosity that whispered,--"
  ],
  [
    "The volume of Jupiter is about 1300 times that of the earth , _ i . e ._ it would take 1300 earth s rolled into one to equal Jupiter in size . But its mean density is slightly less than one quarter of the earth 's , so that its mass is only 316 times greater than the earth 's . The force of gravity on its surface is 2 . 64 times the earth 's . A body weighing 100 pounds on the earth would weigh 264 pounds on Jupiter . It will be observed that Jupiter 's mean density is very nearly the same as that of the sun , and we conclude that it cannot be a solid , rigid globe like the earth . This conclusion is made certain by the fact that its period of rotation on its axis is variable , another resemblance to the sun . The equ atorial parts go round in a shorter 🅁 . found been has existence its of evidence direct no , so if but , within nucleus solid a is there that supposed be may It . ator equ the of south or north distance some situated parts than period",
    "The volume of Jupiter is about 1300 times that of the earth, _i.e._ it would take 1300 earths rolled into one to equal Jupiter in size. But its mean density is slightly less than one quarter of the earth's, so that its mass is only 316 times greater than the earth's. The force of gravity on its surface is 2.64 times the earth's. A body weighing 100 pounds on the earth would weigh 264 pounds on Jupiter. It will be observed that Jupiter's mean density is very nearly the same as that of the sun, and we conclude that it cannot be a solid, rigid globe like the earth. This conclusion is made certain by the fact that its period of rotation on its axis is variable, another resemblance to the sun. The equatorial parts go round in a shorter period than parts situated some distance north or south of the equator. It may be supposed that there is a solid nucleus within, but if so, no direct evidence of its existence has been found."
  ],
